<h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>

<p>OpenAI and Mistral are the two managed fine-tuning APIs most commonly used by European teams — OpenAI for quality and tooling depth, Mistral for cost and EU data residency. The headline fact that surprises most people: both use the ChatML format with a <code>messages</code> array and <code>system</code>/<code>user</code>/<code>assistant</code> roles. A dataset validated for OpenAI will pass Mistral's validator with minor adjustments. The formats are close enough that the same JSONL file can often be used for both with zero changes.</p>

<p>The real differences are in special token handling, system prompt conventions, pricing, and platform capabilities — not the base schema.</p>

<h2 id="formats">JSONL Format Comparison</h2>

<h3 id="chatml-openai">OpenAI GPT-4.1 — ChatML</h3>

<pre><code>{`{"messages": [
  {"role": "system", "content": "You are a concise code reviewer."},
  {"role": "user",   "content": "Review this function:\n\ndef add(a, b):\n    return a+b"},
  {"role": "assistant", "content": "Correct. Consider adding type hints: def add(a: int, b: int) -> int."}
]}`}</code></pre>

<p>OpenAI validation rules that matter:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Last message must have <code>"role": "assistant"</code>.</li>
  <li>Roles must be exactly <code>system</code>, <code>user</code>, or <code>assistant</code>.</li>
  <li>System message is optional but must be first if present.</li>
  <li>A <code>name</code> field is permitted on messages for multi-agent datasets.</li>
  <li>Minimum 10 examples; maximum 100,000 per run.</li>
  <li>Maximum 128,000 tokens per example.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="chatml-mistral">Mistral Large 3 — ChatML on La Plateforme</h3>

<pre><code>{`{"messages": [
  {"role": "system", "content": "You are a concise code reviewer."},
  {"role": "user",   "content": "Review this function:\n\ndef add(a, b):\n    return a+b"},
  {"role": "assistant", "content": "Correct. Consider adding type hints: def add(a: int, b: int) -> int."}
]}`}</code></pre>

<p>The schema is visually identical. Mistral's validation rules:</p>
<ul>
  <li>First message must have <code>"role": "user"</code> — the system message is handled separately as a top-level field or prepended by the tokeniser, not as a message in the array.</li>
  <li>Roles <code>system</code>, <code>user</code>, and <code>assistant</code> are accepted, but Mistral's tokeniser injects its own <code>[INST]</code> and <code>[/INST]</code> special tokens around user turns — these must be absent from your JSONL content.</li>
  <li>Maximum 32,768 tokens per example — significantly lower than OpenAI's 128k limit. Long examples need to be truncated or split.</li>
  <li>Minimum 10 examples.</li>
</ul>

<p>The practical consequence: if your dataset has examples exceeding 32,768 tokens, they will pass OpenAI validation and fail Mistral's. Run both validators before committing to a provider. DataPrep's preset selector flags this with a per-line token count.</p>

<h2 id="key-differences">Key Differences</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Feature</th>
      <th>OpenAI GPT-4.1</th>
      <th>Mistral Large 3</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Base format</td>
      <td>ChatML (<code>messages</code> array)</td>
      <td>ChatML (<code>messages</code> array)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>System message in array</td>
      <td>Optional, first position</td>
      <td>First message must be <code>user</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Special tokens in content</td>
      <td>None expected</td>
      <td><code>[INST]</code>/<code>[/INST]</code> must be absent</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Max tokens per example</td>
      <td>128,000</td>
      <td>32,768</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Function / tool calling</td>
      <td>Yes — tool_calls field supported</td>
      <td>Limited — function calling in fine-tune is beta</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Data residency</td>
      <td>US (with EU DPA available)</td>
      <td>EU by default on La Plateforme</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Fine-tuning UI</td>
      <td>Full dashboard, evals, metrics</td>
      <td>CLI and API; lighter dashboard</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Dataset portability</td>
      <td>Hosted checkpoint, no export</td>
      <td>Adapter download available</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The most important compatibility note: because both use <code>messages</code> arrays with the same role strings, a clean OpenAI dataset with no <code>name</code> fields, no tool calls, and examples under 32,768 tokens is a valid Mistral dataset. You can test one dataset against both providers without any conversion step — just change the preset in DataPrep's Convert tab.</p>

