<h2 id="when-to-use">When to Use Each</h2>

<p><strong>Choose OpenAI GPT-4.1 fine-tuning when:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>You need function calling or tool use in fine-tuned responses — OpenAI's implementation is mature and well-documented; Mistral's is still in beta.</li>
  <li>Your examples regularly exceed 32,768 tokens per conversation (long-context tasks, multi-turn transcripts, document-heavy QA).</li>
  <li>You want a full fine-tuning dashboard with training curves, eval metrics, and a/b test utilities without building your own tooling.</li>
  <li>Your team is already deep in the OpenAI ecosystem and switching API dependencies has a real integration cost.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Choose Mistral Large 3 fine-tuning when:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>EU data residency is a hard requirement — GDPR compliance, French CNIL, or company policy that training data must stay in EU infrastructure.</li>
  <li>Training cost is a primary constraint. At $4/M tokens vs $25/M, Mistral is 6x cheaper to train, which matters when you are iterating frequently with large datasets.</li>
  <li>You want to download and version the fine-tuned adapter weights — Mistral allows adapter export; OpenAI keeps weights on their servers.</li>
  <li>Your dataset is under 32,768 tokens per example and you do not need tool calling — in which case the format is identical and migration is trivial.</li>
</ul>

